# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-landscapes-pretty-pictures-nature-theres
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Landscapes are just pretty pictures of nature – there's not much meaning
  behind them."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While landscapes often show beautiful scenery, they can express powerful
  ideas, like climate change, migration, culture, or even identity. Photographers use
  landscapes not just to show what they see, but to say something about how they feel or
  value."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.084219Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-reflection-finding-faults-criticising-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Reflection is only about finding faults or criticising your work."@en ;
  curric:correction """Reflection is about recognising both strengths and areas to improve in order
  to grow as an artist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-annotation-long-written-paragraphs
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Annotation has to be long, written paragraphs."@en ;
  curric:correction """Annotation can be short notes, labels, sketches, diagrams, or even audio
  recordings. It’s any way you add extra information to explain your ideas clearly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.087318Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-take-inspiration-one-source
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All artists take inspiration from one source."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists might take inspiration from a wide range of sources including
  surroundings, objects, personal experiences, memories, artist's work or historical and
  contemporary movements."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.089903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-good-portfolio-presentation-highly-decorative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A good portfolio presentation should be is highly decorative and colourful to
  be engaging."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While creative touches like washi tape or coloured paint can add personality,
  a clean and minimal layout can be just as effective, sometimes even more so. The goal is
  to curate a cohesive presentation that supports your work, not distracts from it"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-silhouette-means-shadow-outline-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Silhouette just means a shadow or outline — it doesn’t really matter in
  textile design."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Silhouette is essential in textiles — it defines shape, structure and how a
  garment or piece interacts with light and contrast. Designers use silhouettes to make bold
  visual statements, create mood and control how the textile is seen in space."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inside-outside-means-indoors-outdoors
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Inside and outside just means indoors and outdoors."@en ;
  curric:correction """Inside and outside can also mean emotional states, identity, or private vs
  public. Artists use space, scale, and materials to explore physical and psychological
  boundaries."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090586Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-natural-forms-perfectly-symmetrical-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Natural forms are always perfectly symmetrical, like leaves or flowers."@en ;
  curric:correction """While some natural forms show symmetry, most have irregular, flowing shapes.
  Even symmetrical forms often have variations, this is part of what makes nature
  interesting to photographers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090653Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-expensive-professional-materials-automatically-produce
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Expensive or professional materials automatically produce better artwork."@en ;
  curric:correction """The quality of the outcome depends more on how materials are used, combined,
  and manipulated, rather than their cost or brand."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.090766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-balance-means-everything-perfectly-symmetrical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Balance means everything must be perfectly symmetrical."@en ;
  curric:correction """Balance can be symmetrical, but it can also be asymmetrical or radial.
  Asymmetrical balance uses different elements on each side to create visual stability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091524Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-objects-art-depicted-realistic-pictures
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Objects in art are only depicted in realistic pictures."@en ;
  curric:correction """Objects can be used in a range of ways in art. Objects can be used as a
  textile art material or as the subject of an artwork. Objects in art often contain
  symbolic meanings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.091701Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-animation-drawing-moving-pictures-quickly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Animation is just drawing moving pictures quickly."@en ;
  curric:correction """Animation is carefully planned, using frames, keyframes, and digital tools to
  control timing, pace, and movement."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093116Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-casts-look-same-matter-material
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All casts look the same no matter what material is used."@en ;
  curric:correction """Different materials give different textures, weights, weights and finishes -
  same mould different outcomes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093121Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-assemblage-sticking-things-together-randomly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Assemblage is just sticking things together randomly."@en ;
  curric:correction """Assemblage is not random; artists carefully plan how objects interact. Each
  choice affects rhythm, meaning, balance and stability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.093126Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-professional-curators-decide-exhibited
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only professional curators decide what is exhibited."@en ;
  curric:correction """Throughout history and globally, artists have curated their own work.
  Sometimes artists self-curate but sometimes this process can be in collaboration with
  professional curators."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094085Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-paint-mistake-darker-colour-fix
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can paint over a mistake with a darker colour to fix it."@en ;
  curric:correction """In watercolour, layering too many dark colours can muddy the painting. It’s
  better to plan ahead, work from light to dark and use clean water and controlled layers to
  avoid errors."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094413Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-clay-sculptures-finished-once-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Clay Sculptures are finished once the shape is made."@en ;
  curric:correction """Clay work is a process; refinment, moisture control and surface texture are
  key to a finished sculpture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094768Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-2d-drawings-cannot-transformed-3d
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "2D drawings cannot be transformed into 3D forms."@en ;
  curric:correction """2D drawings are like a blueprint for 3D forms. By imagining how shapes in a
  drawing could extend into space, students can add depth, volume, and perspective to give
  their designs a 3D appearance."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094774Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-take-forward-suggestions-your-critique
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """You should take forward all of the suggestions from your critique to improve
  your response."""@en ;
  curric:correction """You should listen to and consider all suggestions carefully, but you are
  expected to respond in a personal and meaningful way, so trust in your own artistic voice.
  You should take the suggestions forward if they align with your vision and style."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095679Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-particular-way-present-art
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """There is one particular way to present art research and it has to look
  polished."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Artist research should be meaningful, it may look polished, but it may also
  just look purposeful and be presented with care."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095688Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-lesson-photography-capturing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception about this lesson is that photography is just about
  capturing what you see, when in fact it involves making creative choices."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Photography is about deciding how to show the subject to communicate an idea
  or feeling. Understanding that really opens up creative possibilities."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095801Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-make-multiple-identical-prints-one
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can make multiple identical prints from one monotype plate."@en ;
  curric:correction """Monotypes create a single, original image. You can sometimes pull a faint
  ghost print after the first, but it’s never identical. The unique nature is what makes
  monotype special."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095852Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-ink-applied-cant-lightened
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once ink is applied it can't be lightened as it is permanent."@en ;
  curric:correction """While ink is permanent when dry, it can be diluted with water whilst wet to
  create lighter values, washes, and gradients."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095858Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-graphic-design-mostly-digital-nature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Graphic design is mostly digital, so nature isn’t really relevant."@en ;
  curric:correction """Graphic design often draws from organic, natural inspiration - many
  professional designs use textures, forms, and concepts from nature to create emotional or
  symbolic meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096741Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-expensive-traditional-materials-better-making
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Expensive or traditional materials are better for making sculptures."@en ;
  curric:correction """Any material can be powerful in sculpture if it supports the concept or
  message being expressed."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.096945Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-unconventional-materials-doesnt-deeper
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Using unconventional materials doesn’t have a deeper purpose in the drawing
  process."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Unconventional materials can lead to unique textures, effects, and creative
  outcomes, challenging traditional drawing methods."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097365Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-iron-wax-dyeing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You don’t have to iron off the wax after dyeing."@en ;
  curric:correction """If you don't iron off the wax after dyeing, the fabric will look unfinished
  and waxy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097375Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-image-internet-print-clearly-large
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any image from the internet will print clearly at large scale."@en ;
  curric:correction """Resolution and image type matter - a raster image may pixelate when enlarged,
  while vector graphics remain sharp."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097780Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-negative-life-experiences-cannot-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Negative life experiences cannot be used as inspiration for creating
  artwork."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Many artists find that exploring difficult life experiences can lead to
  meaningful creative work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097785Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-reproduction-possible-photocopier-printer-reproductions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Reproduction is only possible with a photocopier/printer and reproductions are
  not as valid as originals."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Hand-made reproductions (drawn, traced, collaged, reinterpreted) are also
  valid artistic processes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097802Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-style-something-figure-immediately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Style is something that you have to figure out immediately."@en ;
  curric:correction """Your textile style will grow and change as you explore materials, artists and
  your own ideas. You don’t have to know it yet."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098171Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-watercolours-opaque-used-solid-blocks
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Watercolours are opaque and used for solid blocks of colour."@en ;
  curric:correction """Watercolours are actually transparent and unpredictable, with the paper
  providing the lightest value."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098186Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-make-lots-different-versions-present
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """I can just make lots of different versions and present them as
  experiments."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Experimentation is about thinking through doing. It is only useful when it
  moves your creative journey forward."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098192Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-way-show-your-work-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The way you show your work doesn't really matter so long as it's tidy."@en ;
  curric:correction """A creative, careful presentation will support the idea, message or mood and
  help make your work impactful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098200Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-printmaking-follow-strict-rules-cant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Printmaking has to follow strict rules and can’t be creative or
  experimental."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists can experiment with texture, layering, colour and materials; like
  using different surfaces to print onto or combining different printing methods, to develop
  unique and expressive outcomes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099176Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-base-layer-doesnt-matter-painting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The base layer doesn't matter in painting."@en ;
  curric:correction """A strong base layer, or ground, sets tone, mood, and unity. It can shape the
  whole piece visually and emotionally."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099591Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mixed-media-means-using-random
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Mixed media just means using any random materials together, it doesn’t really
  matter what you choose."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Mixed media is intentional. Each material or technique is chosen for a
  reason, either to add texture, create contrast, or express an idea or emotion. Artists
  think carefully about how the materials work together to enhance the artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099596Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-critical-analysis-art-writing-facts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Critical analysis in art is just about writing facts about artists."@en ;
  curric:correction """Critical analysis goes beyond facts; it involves interpreting the artwork,
  understanding its context, and evaluating its impact and meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101532Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-exploring-different-perspectives-means-drawing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Exploring different perspectives just means drawing the object from different
  angles."""@en ;
  curric:correction """To explore perspectives, you also need to change how you look at the
  object—by positioning yourself differently, changing your distance, or experimenting with
  different materials and techniques. It's about seeing the object in new ways."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-distorting-photograph-manipulation-techniques-damages
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Distorting a photograph with manipulation techniques only damages it."@en ;
  curric:correction """In art, photos are not just static records of the past; they are versatile
  tools that can be reinterpreted and manipulated to express new ideas and perspectives."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101557Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-higher-resolution-makes-digital-artwork
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Higher resolution always makes digital artwork better."@en ;
  curric:correction """Higher resolution increases detail but may not improve design choices; strong
  composition and contrast matter more for impact."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101593Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cyanotype-images-appear-instantly-sun
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Cyanotype images always appear instantly after sun exposure."@en ;
  curric:correction """The image develops gradually and deepens in colour after rinsing and drying;
  exposure time and sunlight intensity affect results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101599Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photo-manipulation-applying-filters
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Photo manipulation is just applying filters."@en ;
  curric:correction """Filters are quick presets, but artful digital manipulation involves
  purposeful use of tools (layers, selections, cloning, adjustments) to control outcome and
  meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101605Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-centering-subject-best
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Centering the subject is always best."@en ;
  curric:correction """Placing the focal point dead centre can make the painting feel static or
  dull. Using the Rule of Thirds or Golden Ratio often creates more dynamic, engaging
  compositions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101625Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-graphic-design-done-computers-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Graphic design is only done on computers and doesn’t involve drawing or
  observational skills."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Graphic design often begins with hand-drawn ideas, including observational
  drawing. Understanding shape, form, and composition from real objects improves digital
  outcomes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101656Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-camera-setting-capture-light-drawings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any camera setting will capture light drawings."@en ;
  curric:correction """Long exposure (slow shutter speed) is essential for creating light drawings,
  without it, the camera won’t capture light movement, only still images."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101864Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-monoprints-look-perfect-repeatable-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Monoprints should look “perfect” and repeatable, like digital prints."@en ;
  curric:correction """Monoprints are valued for their unique, imperfect, and expressive qualities
  that cannot be exactly replicated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.102954Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-basic-clay-techniques-like-pinch
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Basic clay techniques like pinch or coil are only for beginners."@en ;
  curric:correction """Simple clay techniques can be used to build complex and expressive sculptural
  forms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103365Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-3d-sculptural-work-mass-much
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """In 3D or sculptural work, mass is just about how much it weighs and its
  physical presence."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Mass can be symbolic due to the materials used. Materials can carry more or
  less visual weight."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103370Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-portraits-someone-looks-like-theyre
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Portraits are just about what someone looks like - they’re mainly about
  getting the likeness right."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While capturing someone’s physical appearance can be part of a portrait,
  artists often go much deeper. Portraits can reveal who someone is, exploring culture,
  identity, relationships, life experiences and even social or political themes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104279Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-colour-universal-meanings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that colour has universal meanings."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that colour has different symbolic meaning around the
  world."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104297Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photo-editing-obvious-fake
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Photo editing is always obvious or “fake”."@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, edits can be extremely subtle and still have a significant impact
  on the final image."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.104588Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-unlike-artists-graphic-designers-personal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Unlike artists, a graphic designer's personal experiences and preferences have
  no influence on their work and style."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The designer’s individual experiences, interests, and aesthetic preferences
  play a role in shaping a designer's unique style."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105485Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-composition-relevant-2d-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Composition is more relevant to 2D work."@en ;
  curric:correction """Composition is relevant to all areas of art practice as it's about deciding
  on the best arrangement for your work. It will be dictated by your intentions for the
  piece. In 3D, we consider the composition from all angles or in the round."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105652Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-fixed-idea-start-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists always have a fixed idea before they start their work."@en ;
  curric:correction """Many artists gather inspiration as they go. Collecting a wide range of visual
  sources lets ideas evolve naturally rather than sticking to a single idea."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105663Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sculpture-outside-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sculpture is only about the outside shape."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sculpture also uses negative space, scale and proportion to create meaning
  and viewer impact."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105709Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sketchbooks-capture-final-outcomes-perfect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sketchbooks capture final outcomes and perfect work"@en ;
  curric:correction """Sketchbooks capture not only the final outcomes but also the processes and
  innovations behind more finished works."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105715Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-your-work-needs-full-obvious
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Your work needs to be full of obvious pattern for it to feel unified."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pattern is an important element in art but unity can be felt without artwork
  looking like a repeat pattern."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-collaborative-artwork-ends-group-finishes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Collaborative artwork ends when the group finishes working together."@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, collaborative pieces continue to evolve as viewers engage with
  them, as participants reflect on the process and as the artwork is displayed or adapted in
  new contexts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-theme-limits-creativity-because-stick
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A theme limits creativity because you have to stick to one idea."@en ;
  curric:correction """Themes are broad starting points, allowing many creative directions and
  personal interpretations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105805Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-stitching-securing-fabric-pieces-together
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Stitching is for securing fabric pieces together so the type of stitch should
  be uniform."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Using a variety of embroidery stitches when creating a refined sample creates
  visual interest, contrast, texture and depth to the design."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106432Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-main-subject-photo-completely-dominate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The main subject photo should completely dominate the composition."@en ;
  curric:correction """The photograph should interact with the background, not overpower it. The
  transparency of acetate or digital opacity allows the viewer to still appreciate the
  layers beneath. The photograph should complement the painted background, not mask it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106460Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-obvious-explore-theme-reponses-similar
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "It should be obvious how to explore a theme and reponses will be similar."@en ;
  curric:correction """Every person brings their own experiences to a theme so which aspect and how
  you explore it will depend on you, your background and your unique artistic voice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106465Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-need-drawings-textile-project
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You don't need drawings in a textile project."@en ;
  curric:correction """Drawing motifs and sketching developmental ideas during the initial stages in
  design work helps to consolidate ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106552Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-principles-textiles-apply-fashion
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The principles of textiles only apply to fashion"@en ;
  curric:correction """The principles of textiles apply to interiors, art, and technical
  textiles."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.107997Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-thematic-development-means-use-many
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Thematic development means I have to use as many different ideas as possible
  to make my work interesting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Actually, thematic development is about refining ideas so your motifs and
  techniques feel connected. Too many unrelated ideas can make a design look chaotic —
  repeating and varying motifs from one clear theme helps create cohesion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-reimagining-work-means-simply-copying
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Reimagining work means simply copying the original in a slightly different
  way."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Reimagining is about transforming the original work, changing materials,
  scale, techniques, or context to create something new that still connects back to the
  starting point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.108036Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-graphic-design-landscapes-look-realistic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Graphic design landscapes must look realistic to be effective."@en ;
  curric:correction """In graphic communication, the goal is to communicate visually, not replicate
  reality. Stylised or abstracted landscapes can be more impactful and expressive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110119Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lighting-technical-tool-photography
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lighting is just a technical tool in photography."@en ;
  curric:correction """Lighting has the power to transform a photograph, shaping its mood, tone, and
  clarity."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110436Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-changing-aperture-shutter-speed-affects
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Changing the aperture or shutter speed only affects how bright the
  photo is."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While both aperture and shutter speed do affect exposure (how light or dark a
  photo is), they also have creative effects on how the photo looks, such as blur."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110826Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-promoting-show-putting-poster-posting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Promoting a show is just about putting up a poster or posting once online."@en ;
  curric:correction """Effective promotion requires planning, multiple methods, and consistent
  communication."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110926Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-textile-artist-research-pages-decorative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Textile artist research pages have to be decorative to be good."@en ;
  curric:correction """A strong research page is not about decoration — it's about clear
  organisation, relevant visual responses and thoughtful annotations that show understanding
  of the artist’s work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110938Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-technical-aspects-art
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception about technical aspects in art is that technical skill
  only means making artworks look realistic."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Technical skill also includes mastery of materials, control of techniques and
  the ability to use those skills effectively in any style, whether abstract, expressive, or
  conceptual."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110943Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-surface-texture-decoration-doesnt-really
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Surface texture is just decoration and doesn’t really matter."@en ;
  curric:correction """Surface texture plays a key role in communicating meaning, mood, or identity
  in sculpture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110949Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ink-applied-raised-surface-plate
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The ink should be applied only to the raised surface of the plate."@en ;
  curric:correction """In intaglio printing, the recessed lines hold the ink - the surface must be
  wiped clean so only incised marks transfer ink to paper."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111565Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-3d-design-things-look
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "3D design is only about how things look."@en ;
  curric:correction """While appearance (aesthetics) is important, 3D design also prioritises
  function, usability and interaction with real space. Especially in product and furniture
  design, how an object works is just as critical as how it looks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111618Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-objects-photography-depicted-realistically
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Objects in photography are only depicted realistically."@en ;
  curric:correction """Objects can be used in a range of ways in photography. Objects in photography
  can be used as a subject that might also contain symbolic meanings."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.112457Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-layers-equal-better-painting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "More layers is equal to a better painting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Quantity doesn’t guarantee quality. Effective layering is about
  intentionality, each layer should serve a purpose, whether it’s adjusting tone, adding
  texture, or enhancing light."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113357Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-safelight-allows-kind-light-darkroom
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The safelight allows any kind of light to be on in the darkroom without
  damaging prints."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The safelight is not a “free pass” for unlimited light exposure and that all
  light exposure must be controlled and time-sensitive."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113369Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-light-dark-used-make-things
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Light and dark are only used to make things look realistic, not to create
  mood."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This overlooks how artists intentionally use contrast to suggest emotion,
  tension, calm, or drama, not just realism."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113772Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-portraits-someone-looks-like-mainly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Portraits are just about what someone looks like and mainly focus on capturing
  a likeness."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While capturing someone’s physical appearance can be part of a portrait,
  artists often go much deeper. Portraits can reveal who someone is, exploring culture,
  identity, relationships, life experiences and even social or political themes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113874Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-experimentation-means-making-new-things
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Experimentation just means making new things each time."@en ;
  curric:correction """When you experiment you are thinking and doing. Always think about what works
  and what new ideas are generated."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113879Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-digital-drawing-doesnt-require-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Digital drawing doesn’t require the same skills as traditional drawing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Core artistic skills like proportion, tone and composition still apply in
  digital artworks. Digital tools simply offer new ways to achieve them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113924Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-use-traditional-art-materials
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """If you don’t use traditional art materials, your work won’t be taken seriously
  or get a high grade."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Art & Design encourages experimentation with a wide range of materials — not
  just pencil, paint and clay. Using unusual or personal materials can strengthen marks if
  they are purposeful, linked to ideas and part of a thoughtful process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114616Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-same-motif-my-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "If I use the same motif, my work will always look the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Using different techniques can change your textile work. A motif may look
  flat when printed, detailed with embroidery, or bold and layered in appliqué. Your choice
  of textile technique changes the way a motif is interpreted."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114633Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-select-artist-because-their-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """I should select an artist because their work looks like the work I would like
  to create."""@en ;
  curric:correction """This is one reason, but more in depth critique will help you select artists
  based on ideas and visual language that can help you make original work that is more
  personal and meaningful to you."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photographers-cant-control-way-movement
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Photographers can't control the way movement is depicted in their
  photographs."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Photographers can freeze action sharply or blur it creatively, depending on
  the photographer’s intent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114912Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sketchbooks-set-format-presented-right
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sketchbooks have a set format, and must be presented in the 'right' way."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sketchbooks are a personal record of your own creative journey, but in the
  GCSE course they also allow you to gain marks, so sometimes we recommend working in a
  certain way to help you achieve."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115155Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-looking-other-photographers-work-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Looking at other photographers’ work doesn’t help you to create your own
  ideas."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Studying other photographers doesn’t mean copying . It helps you learn new
  techniques, discover styles you like and shape your own original ideas with more
  confidence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115448Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-idea-innovative-interdisciplinary
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Every idea must be innovative and interdisciplinary."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sometimes taking ideas and inspiration from others or following a tried and
  tested path moves you forward."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115569Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-portfolios-need-include
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception about portfolios is that you need to include everything
  you've made."""@en ;
  curric:correction """It's much better to select work that clearly shows your ideas, development,
  artistic journey and skills."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115582Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sculptures-people-made-look-realistic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All sculptures of people are just made to look realistic or beautiful."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists often use figures to tell stories, express ideas, or explore
  identity, emotions, or social issues. A figure might be exaggerated, abstract, or symbolic
  to make people think or feel something."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115693Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-drawing-neat-precise-done-traditional
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Drawing always has to be neat, precise, and done with traditional materials
  like pencil."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists can experiment with non-traditional materials and looser techniques
  like splashes, drips and sprays to develop freedom and unexpected results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115719Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-successful-sketchbook-neat-tidy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A successful sketchbook has to be neat and tidy."@en ;
  curric:correction """A creative sketchbook values risk-taking, layering and visible thinking — not
  just clean layouts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115991Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-fine-liners-produce-same-effect
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All fine liners produce the same effect, regardless of nib size."@en ;
  curric:correction """Nib size changes line weight and impacts detail and clarity; thinner nibs are
  better for intricate details, thicker nibs for bold outlines."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116011Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-response-timed-period-marked-stand
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The response from the timed period is marked as a stand alone outcome."@en ;
  curric:correction """The marks are awarded holistically and take in the whole creative process.
  This period is a great way to resolve your ideas and spend time focusing on realising your
  intentions. It shouldn't be incredibly stressful or worry you!"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-harder-push-squeegee-better-print
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The harder you push the squeegee, the better the print."@en ;
  curric:correction """Too much pressure forces excess ink and blurs edges - controlled, even
  pressure produces the sharpest results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-presentation-decoration
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Presentation is just for decoration."@en ;
  curric:correction "Presentation is part of communication, not decoration."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116344Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-take-random-photos-pick-best
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can just take random photos and pick the best ones later."@en ;
  curric:correction """Intentional planning makes each photo stronger and ensures the series works
  as a whole - not just as individual images."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116361Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-3d-drawings-look-exactly-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "3D drawings must look exactly like 2D sketches."@en ;
  curric:correction """3D drawing explores form and space - it’s about expressing line, contour and
  movement in three dimensions, not replicating flat sketches."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116515Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-digital-tools-replace-traditional-printmaking
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Digital tools replace traditional printmaking."@en ;
  curric:correction """Digital tools enhance traditional methods by expanding creative possibilities
  - neither replaces the other."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116543Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-work-same-part-collaborative
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Everyone has to work on the same part of the collaborative art piece at the
  same time."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, collaboration can also mean dividing tasks, working on separate
  elements that are later combined, or contributing in different ways, such as planning,
  designing, making, or assembling."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116563Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-logos-complicated-detailed-look-professional
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Logos have to be complicated and detailed to look professional."@en ;
  curric:correction """The most successful logos are often simple as clear designs are more
  memorable and versatile across different media, formats and sizes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116568Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dont-need-record-failures-lower
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You don't need to record failures as it will lower your GCSE grade."@en ;
  curric:correction """Record all of your experiments, but make it clear in your work that you know
  which ones were successful and take these forward in your creative journey. This is
  evidence of your informed and insightful approach. This will attract a higher mark."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-collaborative-annotation-its
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception about collaborative annotation is that it’s just about
  leaving individual notes side by side."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, the purpose is not only to make comments but to interact with
  each other's ideas, responding, questioning and building connections so that understanding
  is developed collectively rather than in isolation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-depth-field-controled-moving-camera
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Depth of field is only controled by moving the camera nearer or further away
  from the subject."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Depth of field is mainly controlled by adjusting the aperture (f-stop)."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116715Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-phones-produce-high-quality-photos
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Phones produce high quality photos, so photography with cameras is
  redundant"""@en ;
  curric:correction """Phone cameras are powerful, but professional cameras give more control, lens
  options, and depth of field, which matters for creative and technical work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116720Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lighting-photography-accidental
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lighting in photography is accidental."@en ;
  curric:correction """Lighting plays a crucial role in setting the mood and atmosphere of a
  photograph."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116746Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-design-concept-choosing-looks-good
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A design concept is just choosing what looks good."@en ;
  curric:correction """A strong design concept isn’t just about appearance - it reflects a deeper
  idea or message you want to communicate. What you choose to show should connect to your
  personal voice and purpose."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116844Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-editing-image-changes-damages-original
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Editing an image always changes or damages the original file."@en ;
  curric:correction "By using adjustment layers and layer masks, edits are non-destructive."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116920Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photographic-voice-stays-same-whole
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A photographic voice stays the same for the whole of the photographer’s
  lifetime."""@en ;
  curric:correction "A photographic voice is not fixed. It can change, like we do."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.116934Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-digital-manipulation-cheating-inauthentic-art
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Digital manipulation is cheating or inauthentic art."@en ;
  curric:correction """Digital art is a legitimate medium, just like painting or drawing. It
  requires creative decisions and skill - manipulation is a method of artistic expression,
  not a shortcut."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117071Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-crowded-layout-makes-design-look
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A more crowded layout makes the design look more informative or detailed."@en ;
  curric:correction """More elements can overwhelm the viewer. Effective use of empty space and a
  clear hierarchy can increase impact and readability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117076Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-sewing-machine-straight-lines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You can only use a sewing machine for straight lines or joining fabric."@en ;
  curric:correction """With a freehand arm, you can move the fabric in any direction to draw curves,
  lines, and patterns with thread. Artists use this to stitch portraits, text, and textures,
  guiding the fabric by hand like drawing with a pencil."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117093Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dyeing-methods-colour-fabric-evenly
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All dyeing methods colour fabric evenly across the whole surface."@en ;
  curric:correction """Different dyeing methods produce different effects, techniques like
  dip-dyeing, tie-dye, or resist create uneven or patterned results, while immersion dyeing
  can give a more uniform colour."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117277Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-arrangement-elements-effect-overall-effectiveness
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The arrangement of the elements has no effect on the overall effectiveness of
  the composition."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A successful composition creates structure and activates the visual language
  to convey meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117366Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-technically-perfect-pieces-selected-exhibitions
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The most technically perfect pieces should always be selected for
  exhibitions."""@en ;
  curric:correction """An exhibition’s power lies in how the works connect thematically,
  emotionally, and conceptually, not only in technical skill."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-copying-replicating-image-appropriate-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Copying or replicating an image is an appropriate way to use a source."@en ;
  curric:correction """Influence means taking inspiration and transforming it into something new,
  adding your own creative input rather than directly copying."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-research-page-collection-pictures-facts
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A research page is just a collection of pictures and facts."@en ;
  curric:correction """Research pages are not about collecting facts - they’re about showing how you
  understand and respond to a designer’s work through layout, analysis, and visual
  interpretation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117597Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-collaboration-everyone-agree
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception about collaboration is that everyone has to agree on
  every detail or work in the same style for it to succeed."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, differing approaches and opinions can make the final artwork more
  dynamic and original."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117616Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-light-3d-design-functional-used
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Light in 3D design is only functional, used just to illuminate an object."@en ;
  curric:correction """While light can serve a practical purpose, in 3D design it is also a creative
  tool. It influences mood, draws attention to key areas and enhances the way forms and
  textures are perceived. Light can be as expressive as colour or shape."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117631Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-appliqu-involve-stitching
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Appliqué must involve stitching."@en ;
  curric:correction """Stitching fabric shapes onto a background is a common way to attach pieces in
  appliqué. However, appliqué can also involve using fabric glue or PVA glue to attach
  smaller pieces of fabric to a larger background."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117648Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-fabric-manipulation-used-make-clothes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Fabric manipulation is only used to make clothes look more decorative."@en ;
  curric:correction """Fabric manipulation does add decoration, but it can also change the structure
  of fabric. Techniques like ruching, folding, or layering can give garments shape, volume,
  and movement, not just surface detail."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117716Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-new-resources-my-response
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I need new resources for my response."@en ;
  curric:correction """You need suitable resources, ideally first-hand. They don't need to be new
  they can be sourced from bits of your project so far."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117729Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-themes-photography-interpreted-same-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Themes in photography are interpreted in the same way by all
  photographers."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Themes in photography can inspire creativity while allowing for individual
  interpretation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117863Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-use-skectchbooks
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only artists use skectchbooks."@en ;
  curric:correction """Both artists and graphic designers use sketchbooks for creative exploration.
  The way they use them may differ in purpose, content, and process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.117871Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-elements-principles-art-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The elements and principles of art are the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that the core principles are: balance, movement, rhythm,
  pattern, contrast, unity, emphasis. The elements are the components that artists use to
  create an artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.118290Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-make-art-their-intenral
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All artists make art about their intenral and external influences."@en ;
  curric:correction """Some artists make art that is obviously about their influences and some
  don't."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.118516Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-making-exhibition-hanging-art
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Making an exhibition is just about hanging art."@en ;
  curric:correction """Curation requires skills and knowledge. Curation can create connections and a
  narrative between individual works."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.118522Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-constructed-textiles-made-weaving-loom
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Constructed textiles are only made by weaving on a loom."@en ;
  curric:correction """Constructed textiles include any fabric created by interlacing, knotting,
  looping, or bonding fibres such as weaving, knitting, crochet, macramé and even non-woven
  techniques, not just loom weaving."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119093Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-designers-style-fixed-remains-constant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A designer's style is fixed and remains constant."@en ;
  curric:correction """A designer will grow and develop and so their distinctive style will evolve
  over time as they experiment more and engage with new ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119143Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-concept-entirely-fixed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A concept is entirely fixed."@en ;
  curric:correction """A concept can develop and evolve but it should not completely change without
  very good reason."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119168Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-final-piece-copy-designers-style
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The final piece should just copy the designer’s style."@en ;
  curric:correction """While your chosen designer should influence your work, the final piece should
  show your own creative voice. Think about what you want to communicate, and how the
  designer’s style can help you do that - not just replicate it."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119216Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-experimentation-making-something-perfect-finished
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Experimentation is only about making something perfect or a finished
  product."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Experimentation is about exploring and learning through trial and error.
  Showing how you develop your ideas is key to finding your textile voice."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119230Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-patterns-need-regular-ordered
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Patterns need to be regular and ordered."@en ;
  curric:correction "Pattern can be irregular or regular."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119632Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-art-materials-dont-matter-beyond
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Art materials don’t matter beyond how they look or feel."@en ;
  curric:correction """Materials can carry deep personal and cultural meanings that add important
  layers to the artwork’s story and message."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cannot-remove-work-your-book
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You cannot remove any work from your book or portfolio."@en ;
  curric:correction """You should select your work carefully and on rare occasions you might find
  work that doesn't add to the creative journey and is best left out. Discuss these pieces
  with your teacher to get guidance first."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119655Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-concept-something-complex-deep-valid
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A concept has to be something complex or deep to be valid."@en ;
  curric:correction """Strong concepts can be simple but meaningful. The key is personal connection
  and clarity of intent."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119820Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-common-misconception-paint-pouring-its
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A common misconception about paint pouring is that it’s purely random and
  anyone can do it without skill."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In reality, while paint pouring involves chance, artists use technique,
  colour theory and control to create intentional and successful compositions. It’s both
  creative and technical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.119941Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-graphic-communication-mainly-making-things
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Graphic communication is mainly about making things look pretty."@en ;
  curric:correction """While aesthetics are important, graphic communication focuses on conveying
  information effectively through visual principles like balance, hierarchy and alignment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.120440Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-choosing-intresting-materials-shapes-enough
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Choosing intresting materials or shapes is enough to make a sculpture
  'meaningful'."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A sculpture is powerful when choices are intentional. Materials, forms, and
  symbols must link clearly to a theme; without this, the work can feel random instead of
  meaningful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.120795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-experiments-include-radical-exaggerated-changes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Experiments should include radical or very exaggerated changes."@en ;
  curric:correction """You can make very subtle changes and experiements and they can have a big
  impact on your work - that's the value of experimentation!"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.120807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-portraits-someone-looks-like-surface
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Portraits are just about what someone looks like on the surface with no deeper
  meaning."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While capturing someone’s physical appearance can be part of a portrait,
  photographers often go much deeper. Portraits can reveal who someone is, exploring
  culture, identity, relationships, life experiences and even social or political themes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.122761Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-research-separate-making-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Research is separate from making work."@en ;
  curric:correction "Research feeds directly into experimentation and outcomes."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.122788Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-your-textile-concept-look-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Your textile concept has to look like your artist’s work."@en ;
  curric:correction """A strong artist response adapts inspiration to create something new and
  personal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123050Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-sculpture-realistic-life-like-considered
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Sculpture must be realistic or life-like to be considered good."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sculpture can be abstract or symbolic, focusing on space, balance, and
  movement rather than realism."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123076Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-designing-response-theme-means-drawing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Designing in response to a theme means drawing something direct or
  literal."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Themes are open to interpretation - good design often uses symbolism,
  abstraction and personal meaning to create deeper, more thoughtful responses."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123247Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-final-piece-large-scale-completely
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A final piece must be large scale and completely finished."@en ;
  curric:correction """A final piece or outcome is just the end point in your journey so far, it
  should resolve your ideas but it can do this in many ways and in different scales."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123373Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-group-crit-useful-while-project
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A group crit is only useful while the project is ongoing."@en ;
  curric:correction """A group crit involves diverse perspectives. Even if you don’t incorporate it
  into your current work, it helps you understand different viewpoints to improve your
  skills and help you anticipate opinions in future projects, making you a better artist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.123442Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-dry-media-used-fine-detailed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Dry media can only be used for fine, detailed work."@en ;
  curric:correction """Dry media is highly versatile and can be used for bold, expressive textures
  and atmospheric effects, not just for precision."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124064Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-found-materials-junk-dont-belong
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Found materials are just junk and don’t belong in real artwork."@en ;
  curric:correction """Found materials bring unique textures and personal or cultural meaning to a
  sculpture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124332Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-cardboard-weak-build-strong-structures
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Cardboard is too weak to build strong structures."@en ;
  curric:correction """Cardboard becomes structurally strong when layered, folded or rolled. It is
  even used in architecture and furniture design for its surprising durability."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124340Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-paper-canvas-proper-professional-surfaces
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only paper and canvas are proper or professional surfaces for making art"@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists have long worked on a wide range of surfaces, including wood, metal,
  glass, fabric, cardboard, plastic, ceramics, and more. The surface is a creative choice,
  not a limitation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-final-piece-big-completely-different
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A final piece has to be big or completely different from my previous work."@en ;
  curric:correction """A strong final piece develops from your earlier ideas. It doesn’t need to be
  large or totally new — thoughtful refinement, consistent concept and clear links to your
  research and samples are what matter most."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124352Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mixed-media-means-throwing-lots
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Mixed media just means throwing lots of materials together."@en ;
  curric:correction """Each material should have a purpose — it must add meaning or structure, not
  just make it look busy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pour-plaster-once-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "I can just pour all the plaster at once and it will work."@en ;
  curric:correction """Plaster heats as it sets and pouring too much at once can trap air, cause
  cracks or damage the model. Layering ensures detail and structure."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124782Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-first-hand-observations-drawings
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "First-hand observations have to be drawings"@en ;
  curric:correction """First-hand observations can also include photography, sound recordings,
  writing, collected objects, or video — any direct response to real-life experiences."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124840Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-ink-produces-stronger-better-prints
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "More ink always produces stronger, better prints."@en ;
  curric:correction """Too much ink causes smudging and loss of detail; even, thin layers produce
  cleaner and sharper results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.124854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-printing-copying-replicating-image
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Printing is only about copying or replicating an image."@en ;
  curric:correction """Printing is a creative process where choices about technique, layering, and
  texture produce unique outcomes - even when using the same plate or block."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125520Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-surface-pattern-decoration-used-textiles
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Surface pattern decoration is only used in textiles."@en ;
  curric:correction """Surface pattern can be applied to many materials, including ceramics,
  wallpaper, furniture, and architecture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125537Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-surface-works-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think any surface works the same and that there is one correct tool
  for painting."""@en ;
  curric:correction """There’s no single “right” tool. Brushes give precision, while palette knives,
  sponges, or fingers add texture. The surface also matters. Paper absorbs, primed canvas
  holds paint, and board gives smooth results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.125907Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-architecture-making-buildings-look-nice
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Architecture is just about making buildings look nice, not about solving
  problems or reflecting culture."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Architecture is about much more than appearance. It solves practical problems
  like shelter and space, and reflects cultural values, history, and how people live."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.126244Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-jump-straight-inspiration-finished
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists jump straight from inspiration to a finished artwork."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists spend significant time experimenting, revising, and refining their
  ideas before arriving at a final piece."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.127201Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-text-work-long-its-readable
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any text will work as long as it’s readable."@en ;
  curric:correction """Typography must be chosen and placed purposefully to support the tone,
  audience and message - readability is just the starting point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.128499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-make-something-personal-cant-copy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """As I have to make something personal I can't copy an artist's ideas or
  techniques."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Copying or pastiche can help you learn techniques, but to create original
  work that meets the A04 objective, you must also add your own ideas and intentions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.129579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-source-something-copy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "A source is just something to copy."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sources are not meant to be copied. They act as a starting point for
  creativity. Designers explore a source’s shapes, patterns, colours, or meanings and
  reinterpret them to create original work that reflects their own ideas and context."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.129782Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-surface-decoration-added-end-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Surface decoration should be added at the end and doesn’t need much
  thought."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Surface design should be planned and integrated to reflect and enhance the
  sculptural idea."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131034Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-digital-brushes-automatically-makes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Using digital brushes automatically makes artwork look realistic."@en ;
  curric:correction """Realism depends on how brush settings, layering and blending are applied -
  not the tool itself. Technique and practice are crucial."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131090Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-themes-art-interpreted-same-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Themes in art are interpreted in the same way by all artists"@en ;
  curric:correction """Themes in art can inspire creativity while allowing for individual
  interpretation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131894Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-talk-their-work-promote
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists only talk about their work to promote it in galleries and museums."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists might talk about their work for engagement and promotion, in a
  variety of contexts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.132346Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-3d-design-making-things-look
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """3D design is just about making things look good, it doesn't need to express
  deeper ideas."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While aesthetics are important, 3D design is also a powerful way to
  communicate ideas and solve problems. It can explore complex themes through physical form,
  material choice, and spatial design. Good design combines purpose with meaning."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.132363Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inside-outside-design-refers-physical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """\"Inside\" and \"outside\" in design always refers to physical spaces, like
  buildings or rooms."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In design, \"inside\" and \"outside\" can mean more than places — they can
  show how someone feels on the inside, how people hide emotions, or the contrast between
  personal and public life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.132374Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-photo-drawing-finished-cant
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Once a photo or drawing is finished, it can’t be changed or developed
  further."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A finished photo or drawing is just a starting point—artists often rework,
  edit, layer, or translate their images into new forms using different media to explore
  deeper meaning or fresh creative directions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133362Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-material-artist-uses-doesnt-matter
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """The material an artist uses doesn’t matter as long as the subject or idea is
  strong."""@en ;
  curric:correction """The choice of materials greatly affects how an artwork looks, feels and
  communicates meaning. Materials can add texture, symbolism and emotional impact that
  deepen the viewer’s understanding."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133368Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-carving-chipping-randomly-until-shape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Carving is just about 'chipping away' randomly until a shape appears."@en ;
  curric:correction """Skilled carving is deliberate - starting with planning, respecting grain, and
  refining in controlled stages."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133376Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shapes-found-positive-space-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Shapes are only found in the positive space made by an actual object."@en ;
  curric:correction """Shapes are inadvertently created all the time in the gaps between objects in
  your composition. We call this the negative space."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133391Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-graphic-desingers-use-digtial-tools
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Graphic desingers only use digtial tools."@en ;
  curric:correction """Traditional approaches to graphic design existed before digital tools and are
  still widely used today."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133877Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-digital-art-lacks-creativity-authenticity
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Digital art lacks the creativity or authenticity of traditional methods."@en ;
  curric:correction """Digital tools expand, rather than replace, creativity. Artists can blend
  hand-drawn, painted, or textured work into digital layers to achieve unique results."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.134937Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-talk-visual-elements-principles-art
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """I should talk about all of the visual elements and principles of art in my
  evaluation."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Select and describe only the areas that are relevant, but consider them all
  to see if you notice anything new. Sometimes you make work instinctively and don't realise
  until later what techniques or principles you actually applied."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.135409Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-documenting-artists-journey-completed-artworks
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Documenting an artist’s journey is only about completed artworks."@en ;
  curric:correction """Sketchbooks, notes, and drafts are just as important, showing the development
  of ideas, experimentation, and problem-solving along the way."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.136181Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-charcoal-messy-hard-control-its
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Charcoal is messy and hard to control, so it's not suitable for detailed or
  serious artwork."""@en ;
  curric:correction """While charcoal can be loose and expressive, with practice it can also be
  controlled for fine detail. Artists often use different types of charcoal (e.g. vine for
  light sketching, compressed for deep blacks) to achieve a full range of effects."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139279Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-plastic-bags-cannot-used-weaving
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Plastic bags cannot be used in weaving because they are too soft."@en ;
  curric:correction """Nearly all materials can be used to weave with as long as they are cut
  correctly so that they can fit into the loom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139291Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-lines-useful-drawing-painting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Lines are only useful in drawing and painting"@en ;
  curric:correction """Lines are vital for all work across every specialism. There are many ways
  line can impact your work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139297Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-using-inspiration-artists-means-copying
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Using inspiration from artists means copying their work exactly."@en ;
  curric:correction """The goal is not to copy an artist's work but to adapt their techniques,
  mark-making, or approach to develop your own creative style and ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139748Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-texture-visual-quality-doesnt-add
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Texture is only a visual quality, it doesn't add meaning to your work."@en ;
  curric:correction """Texture is one of the tools artists use as a visual language to
  communicate."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139760Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-making-mistakes-art-bad-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Making mistakes in art is always bad for your artistic development."@en ;
  curric:correction "Mistakes and experimentation can lead to developing an artistic voice."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140274Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-brushes-used-painting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that only brushes are used in painting."@en ;
  curric:correction """Through modelling and explanation - remind pupils that there are a range of
  painting tools and materials that can be used to apply paint to a surface."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140518Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hand-stitching-old-fashioned-traditional
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hand stitching is only for old-fashioned or traditional designs."@en ;
  curric:correction """Hand stitching is a versatile skill that allows designers to add personal,
  creative and intricate details that machines often can’t replicate. It’s valued in modern
  fashion and art for its unique, handmade quality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140524Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-detail-makes-artwork-better
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "More detail always makes an artwork better."@en ;
  curric:correction """Too much detail—especially if it’s unfocused—can make an artwork feel
  cluttered, overwhelming, or take attention away from the focal point."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140532Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-photography-journals-book-form
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Photography journals are always in book form."@en ;
  curric:correction """They can also exist digitally or as collections of images, notes, and
  sketches in various formats."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-natural-forms-used-make-things
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Natural forms are just used to make things look pretty; they don’t have real
  purpose in design."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Natural forms can inspire smart, efficient and eco-friendly designs through
  biomimicry. For example, the form of a bird’s wing has influenced airplane design. Artists
  can use natural forms to solve problems and raise awareness about the environment."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142865Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hue-colour-mean-same-thing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hue and colour mean the same thing."@en ;
  curric:correction """Colour is the overarching name for what we see but it is made up of hues and
  tones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142895Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-final-piece-represents-culmination-artists
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """A final piece represents the culmination of an artist's whole life's work, all
  their ideas and all the materials they have ever used."""@en ;
  curric:correction """A final piece represents the culmination of an artist's themes, materials and
  techniques, and artistic voice, at a particular moment in time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147249Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artist-statement-long-formal-piece
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """An artist statement has to be a long, formal piece of writing full of
  complicated words."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Artist statements can be short and simple, written in clear and honest
  language, and can also take other formats such as bullet points, spoken word, visual mind
  maps, captions, or short videos."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149338Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-portraits-graphic-design-look-realistic
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Portraits in graphic design must look realistic to be effective."@en ;
  curric:correction """Graphic design often relies on abstraction and stylisation to communicate
  more clearly and powerfully than realism - effective portraits use design choices to
  enhance meaning, not replicate reality."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149355Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artist-research-making-your-work
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artist research is about making your work like another artist's artwork."@en ;
  curric:correction """Recording and analysing an artist’s work is essential for developing your
  understanding of techniques, concepts, and creative processes. We don't need to copy an
  artist's work but can take and apply knowledge and ideas inspired by relevant artists."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149448Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-wet-media-fully-controlled-neat
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Wet media must always be fully controlled and neat to look professional."@en ;
  curric:correction """Expressive, loose, or even accidental marks can be intentional and valued in
  graphic communication, depending on the project's aims."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150038Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-fonts-communicate-same-message-its
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """All fonts communicate the same message - it’s just about how the
  letters look."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Fonts are like voices - each has a different tone. Choosing a bold, heavy
  font versus a thin, elegant one can completely change how a brand is perceived by the
  viewer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.150044Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-inside-outside-art-refers-physical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """\"Inside\" and \"outside\" in art always refers to physical spaces, like
  buildings or rooms."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In art, \"inside\" and \"outside\" can mean more than places — they can show
  how someone feels on the inside, how people hide emotions, or the contrast between
  personal and public life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.154270Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-transforming-image-means-stretching-resizing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Transforming an image always means stretching or resizing it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Transformation in digital art includes combining, masking, blending, and
  reimagining images - not just changing size or shape."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.154660Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
